04440nam a22006015i 9780674056800DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20102010mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740568007 a10.4159/97806740568002doi  a(DE-B1597)626013  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aDS558b.P745 2006 7aHIS0360602bisacsh04a973.9221 aPreston, Andrew, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe War Council :bMcGeorge Bundy, the NSC, and Vietnam /cAndrew Preston. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 The Mentor: Stimson’s Influence on Bundy -- t2 A Foreign Office in Microcosm: Creating the National Security Adviser and Re-creating the NSC Staff -- t3 Learning to Fear the Bomb: Kennedy’s Crises and the Origins of Détente -- t4 The Hawk: Rostow and the First Attempt at Americanization -- t5 The Soft Hawk: Forrestal and Nonmilitary Escalation -- t6 Bundy the Adviser: The Drift to War -- t7 Bundy the Advocate: The Rush to War -- t8 Bundy Ambivalent: Rolling Thunder, Student Unrest, and the Decision to Commit Troops -- t9 Bundy Resilient: The Bombing Pause and the Continuing Search for a Successful Policy -- tEpilogue: Legacies -- tNotes -- tBibliography of Primary Sources -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWas the Vietnam War unavoidable? Historians have long assumed that ideological views and the momentum of events made American intervention inevitable. By examining the role of McGeorge Bundy and the National Security Council, Andrew Preston demonstrates that policymakers escalated the conflict in Vietnam in the face of internal opposition, external pressures, and a continually failing strategy.Bundy created the position of National Security Adviser as we know it today, with momentous consequences that continue to shape American foreign policy. Both today's presidential supremacy in foreign policy and the contemporary national security bureaucracy find their origins in Bundy's powers as the first National Security Adviser and in the ways in which he and his staff brought about American intervention in Vietnam. Presidents Kennedy and Johnson were not enthusiastic about waging a difficult war in pursuit of murky aims, but the NSC's bureaucratic dexterity and persuasive influence in the Oval Office skewed the debate in favor of the conflict.In challenging the prevailing view of Bundy as a loyal but quietly doubting warrior, Preston also revises our understanding of what it meant--and means--to be a hawk or a dove. The War Council is an illuminating and compelling story with two inseparable themes: the acquisition and consolidation of power; and how that power is exercised.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aVietnam War, 1961-1975xUnited States. 0aVietnam War, 1961-1975zUnited States. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044220540uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674056800?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674056800423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674056800/original  a978-3-11-044220-5  Harvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles